   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The
                           Foundling</title></hi>].<note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"
                                 ><title><title>The Foundling</title>; A Comedy, In Five Acts; By
                                 <ref target="people.html#MooreEdward">Edward Moore</ref>. As
                              Performed at the Theatre Royal, <ref target="people.html#DruryLane"
                                 >Drury Lane</ref>. Printed Under the Authority of the Managers From
                              the Prompt Book. With Remarks by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs"
                                 >Mrs. Inchbald</ref></title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman,
                        Hurst, Rees, and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-5. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title level="m">The British Theatre; or, A Collection of Plays,
                              Which Are Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref>, <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>, and <ref
                                 target="people.html#Haymarket">Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the
                              Authority of the Managers from the Prompt Books. With Biographical and
                              Critical Remarks, by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                                 Inchbald.</ref></title></hi> In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. XIV. <hi
                           rendition="#italics">
                           <title>Man of the World</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>Foundling</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>Gamester</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Roman
                              Father</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#EdwardPrinceofWales">Edward the Black
                                 Prince</ref></title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst,
                        Rees, and Orme, Paternoster Row. 1808. The first performance of this play
                        was staged at the <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Theatre Royal, Drury
                           Lane</ref> on February 13<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi>, 1748. Laura DeWitt
                        and Mary A. Waters edited this essay for <hi rendition="#italics">The
                           Criticism Archive</hi>.</note>
                     <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </title>
               </bibl>
            </head>
            <p><quote><lg type="stanza">
                     <l>From such dull stuff, what profit can you reap?</l>
                     <l>You cry&#8212;"'Tis very fine!" and fall asleep.<note>From the Epilogue of
                           the 1759 edition of <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The
                              Foundling</title></hi>, written by <ref
                              target="people.html#GarrickDavid">David Garrick</ref> and spoken by
                              <ref target="people.html#CibberSusannah">Susannah
                        Cibber</ref>.</note></l>
                  </lg></quote></p>

            <p>Those lines, from the Epilogue, written by <ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid"
                  >Garrick</ref>, have, for the present taste of the town, somewhat too much of
               truth in them: for assuredly "<title>The Foundling</title>" would not, at this
               period, have power to keep an audience from the enjoyment of a comfortable slumber.
               It may, however, be read with pleasure, as a little novel, by which the reader will
               neither be induced to laugh, to weep, nor to admire&#8212;though he may yet be amused
               by a certain degree of interest, attached to the fable and the events. It was the
               first dramatic work of a man, since much esteemed for having produced the tragedy of
                  "<title>The Gamester</title>;" notwithstanding both that, and the present drama,
               met with considerable opposition, on the first night of their
                     representation.<note><hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Foundling</title></hi>
                  was <ref target="people.html#MooreEdward">Moore</ref>'s debut into playwriting.
                     <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Gamester</title></hi> (1753) became <ref
                     target="people.html#MooreEdward">Moore</ref>'s most popular play. <ref
                     target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref> draws the notion of this play's
                  first-night unpopularity from <ref target="people.html#BakerDavid">David Erskine
                     Baker</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Companion to the
                        Play-House</title></hi> (1764, p. unnumbered).</note></p>

            <p>The character of Faddle,<note>Faddle is Young Belmont's crude friend of inferior
                  social class. Young Belmont is both the hero and the rake of the play. Young
                  Belmont has saved Fidelia, the eponymous character and a young woman who was
                  orphaned as a child, from a life of poverty and prostitution, but then plans to
                  have sex with her without offering her marriage and excuse his actions by claiming
                  that she is a whore.</note> in this comedy, was the part at which the audience
               revolted, when it first appeared; and, no doubt, he is a being whose mind is too much
               deformed for public exhibition. <quote><lg type="stanza">
                     <l>&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;Such abject trash,</l>
                     <l>Deserves not satire's, but the hangman's lash.<note>From <ref
                              target="people.html#CibberColley">Colley Cibber</ref>'s Prologue to
                              <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Careless Husband</title></hi>,
                           lines 13-14.</note></l>
                  </lg></quote><fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi></fw><pb n="4"/></p>

            <p>Nor is Young Belmont, the hero of the piece, more than one degree removed from this,
               his friend, in baseness; and that distinction is in the article of courage. For this
               solitary virtue he is allowed, by the author, to be forgiven all his vices, and
               blessed with the hand of the woman he loves;&#8212;yet the play has the reputation of
               containing an excellent moral.</p>

            <p>Sir Charles Raymond, excepting Fidelia, is by far the best drawn character in the
               whole work&#8212;nay, Filedia, perhaps, should give place to him. Their relationship
               is well contrived, and would be more interesting, was the discovery less romantically
               brought about.<note>Sir Charles is a rake who pursues a relationship with Fidelia
                  outside of his marriage.</note></p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#CibberSusannah">Mrs. Cibber</ref>, the idol of the public,
               at the time this comedy first appeared, is said to have been exquisite in the part of
               the Foundling; but it is a character, which requires, in an actress, abilities, so
               little at present in use, that it can be hardly conceived what plaintive, or pathetic
               arts, this performer possessed, to make so insipid a personage have power over the
               hearts of an audience.</p>

            <p>"<title>The Foundling</title>" has been called an imitation of "<title>The Conscious
                  Lovers</title>."<note>In his <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Companion to the
                        Play-House</title></hi>, <ref target="people.html#BakerDavid">David Erskine
                     Baker</ref> writes, "It has not however since that Time been continued as an
                  acting Comedy, being generally considered as bearing too near a resemblance to the
                     <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Conscious Lovers</title></hi>" (1764, p.
                  unnumbered). <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Conscious Lovers</title></hi> by
                     <ref target="people.html#SteeleRichard">Richard Steele</ref> was originally
                  produced in 1722.</note> If it be so, like all imitations, it falls infinitely
               beneath the merit of its original.&#8212;It was first acted in 1748.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#MooreEdward">Mr. Moore</ref>, the author of this play,
               wrote, besides his two dramatic works, "<title>The Trial of Selim, the
                  Persian</title>," a poem, in compliment to <ref
                  target="people.html#LytteltonGeorge">Lord Lyttelton</ref>, which has been praised
               as a most elegant panegyric<note><ref target="people.html#MooreEdward">Moore</ref>
                  published <hi rendition="#italics"><title> The Trial of Selim the Persian, for
                        Divers High Crimes and Misdemeanours</title></hi> (1748) as a defense for
                  his friend and patron <ref target="people.html#LytteltonGeorge">George
                     Lyttelton</ref> against his political opponents.</note>&#8212;and his
                  "<title>Fables for the Female Sex</title>" have been compared with <ref
                  target="people.html#GayJohn">Gay</ref>'s.<note><ref
                     target="people.html#MooreEdward">Moore</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"
                        ><title>Fables for the Female Sex</title></hi> (1744) were modeled after
                     <ref target="people.html#GayJohn">John Gay</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"
                        ><title>Fifty-one Fables in Verse</title></hi> (1727). <ref
                     target="people.html#MooreEdward">Moore</ref>'s fables warned against feminine
                  vices and served as a guide to his conception of proper feminine
               conduct.</note>&#8212;He married a lady, who <pb n="5"/>was herself poetical, and, in
               her maiden state, being deeply in love with her future husband (while her passion was
               a secret both to him and all her friends) her muse prompted her to write a copy of
               verses to a young lady, her cousin, in which were contained the following lines,
               perfectly mysterious; till being shown to a number of persons, and to <ref
                  target="people.html#MooreEdward">Mr. Moore</ref> amongst the rest, he had the
               sagacity to find out the riddle, and the gratitude to reward its fair authoress with
               his hand. <quote><lg type="stanza">
                     <l>Would you think it, my coz, for the fault I must own,</l>
                     <l>Your Jenny, at last, is quite covetous grown:</l>
                     <l>Though millions, if fortune should lavishly pour,</l>
                     <l>I still should be wretched, if I had not More.</l>
                     <l>* * * * * * * * * * * * * * * *</l>
                     <l>You will wonder, my dear, who this charmer be,</l>
                     <l>Whose merit can boast such a conquest as me;</l>
                     <l>But you shan't know his name, though I told you before;</l>
                     <l>It begins with an M&#8212;but I dare not say More.<note>In 1750, <ref
                              target="people.html#MooreEdward">Moore</ref> married Jane Hamilton, a
                           young woman of fortune and herself a poet. This anecdote and poem are
                           found in <ref target="people.html#BellJohn">John Bell</ref>'s <hi
                              rendition="#italics"><title>The Poets of Great Britain Complete from
                                    <ref target="people.html#ChaucerGeoffrey">Chaucer</ref> to <ref
                                    target="people.html#ChurchillCharles"
                              >Churchill</ref></title></hi> (1781, vol. 98, p. viii).</note></l>
                  </lg></quote><fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 3</hi></fw></p>
         </div>
      </body>
